revision.text:
In [[Nonnus]]' ''[[Dionysiaca]]'' (late fourth or early fifth century CE), '''Alpos''' is a [[Sicily|Sicilian]] [[Gigantes|giant]] who terrorized [[Punta del Faro]] and he was killed by [[Dionysus]] with his [[thyrsus]].<ref>Pierre Grimal, ''The Dictionary of Classical Mythology'', ''s.v.'' "Alpos": "Like every giant he was a son of [[Gaia (mythology)|Earth]]".</ref> Like the [[Hecatonchires|Hundred-Handed Ones]] he had many arms, and his head was covered with [[Viperidae|viper]]s, like [[Medusa]]. Alpos, who does not appear elsewhere in [[Greek mythology]], and received no [[Cult (religion)|cult]], may be considered an invention of the fertile imagination of Nonnus.
