{{Refimprove|date=February 2010}}{{Fringe theories|date=June 2018}}[[File:GAZ-21 (2nd series) "Volga" (black colored).jpg|200px|thumb|Black [[Volga (automobile)|Volga]] [[limousine]].]] '''Black Volga''' ({{lang-pl|czarna wołga}}) refers to an [[urban legend]] widespread in [[People's Republic of Poland|Poland]], Hungary, Russia,<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Urban Legends|author=Brunvand, J.H.|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781576070765|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H8Kk7bS66jMC}}</ref> Belarus, Ukraine, and Mongolia,<ref name="google2">{{cite book|title=Bodies: Sex, Violence, Disease, and Death in Contemporary Legend|author=Bennett, G.|year=2009|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|isbn=9781604732450|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rwio_KDGmREC}}</ref> mainly in the 1960s and 1970s.<ref> {{cite web |url=http://serwisy.gazeta.pl/kultura/1,34169,1853428.html |title=Czarna wołga i inne legendy miejskie |publisher=serwisy.gazeta.pl ([[Gazeta Wyborcza]]) |accessdate=2009-06-01 |language=Polish |last= |first= }} </ref><ref> {{cite web |url=http://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/Wiadomosci/1,80708,6353499,Czarna_wolga_w_hipermarkecie.html |title=Czarna wołga w hipermarkecie |publisher=wiadomosci.gazeta.pl ([[Gazeta Wyborcza]]) |accessdate=2009-06-01 |language=Polish |last= |first= }} </ref><ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.dziennik.pl/auto/article9504/Czarna_wolga_ma_50_lat.html |title=Czarna wołga ma 50 lat |publisher=dziennik.pl ([[Dziennik Polska-Europa-Świat|Dziennik]]) |accessdate=2009-06-01 |language=Polish |last= |first= }} </ref><ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.wiadomosci.polska.pl/specdlapolski/article,Miejskie_legendy,id,342292.htm |title=Miejskie legendy |publisher=wiadomosci.polska.pl |accessdate=2009-06-01 |language=Polish |last= |first= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005044651/http://wiadomosci.polska.pl/specdlapolski/article%2CMiejskie_legendy%2Cid%2C342292.htm |archivedate=2008-10-05 |df= }} </ref> It was about a black (or in some versions red<ref name="google"/>) [[Volga (automobile)|Volga]] limousine that was allegedly used to abduct people, especially children.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} According to different versions, it was driven by [[priesthood (Catholic Church)|priests]], [[nun#Roman Catholic|nuns]], [[Jew]]s, [[vampire]]s, [[satanist]]s or [[Satan]] himself.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} The car is described as having white wheel rims, white curtains or other white elements.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
Children were kidnapped to use their blood as a cure for rich Westerners or Arabs<ref name="google2"/> suffering from [[leukemia]]; other variants used [[organ theft]] as the motive, combining it with another famous legend about kidney theft by the [[KGB]]. The legend surfaced again in the late 20th century, with a [[BMW]] or [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]] car taking the Volga's place, sometimes depicted with horns instead of [[wing mirrors]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} In this version, the driver would ask passers-by for the time and kill them when they approached the car to answer. In another version of the legend, the victim would die at the same time a day later.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} Many{{Who|date=June 2018}} suspect{{Original research inline|date=June 2018}} that the story was circulated by the [[Służba Bezpieczeństwa|Polish secret police]] in order to detract validity from stories of real kidnappings by the government.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
