The '''German mines at Caldbeck''' were part of the operations of the [[Society of Mines Royal|Company of Mines Royal]] in [[Caldbeck]], which introduced German miners from modern day [[Austria]] and [[Bavaria]] into the [[Lake District]] in 1563, though earlier works in the area are thought to have been begun in the 1300s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rock-site.co.uk/cms.php?id_cms=18 |title=Caldbeck Fells, Cumbria, England |last= |first= |date= |website=Steetley Minerals |publisher=Peter Briscoe |access-date=4 December 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/Lasting-German-links-with-mines-of-Keswick-and-Coniston-0068ba05-283a-44cc-ac5e-cff3e29a5a3b-ds |title=Lasting German links with mines of Keswick and Coniston|last=Crosby |first=Alan |date= 10 March 2016 |website=The Mail |publisher= CN Group |access-date= 4 December 2017 |quote=}}</ref> The importance of the operation lies in its historical significance as the first large-scale [[copper mining]] and smelting operation in the British Islands which was well-documented. New smelting techniques were introduced which were allowed the treatment of [[argentiferous]] [[copper sulphide]] ores and the more complex lead-copper-silver ores from Caldbeck.
Mining started at Caldbeck in June 1566 but was soon discontinued and was not resumed until 1568, when work continued under the supervision of the [[Hochstetter]] family until around 1630, and then was not resumed until around 1695. The identity of the principal copper mines near [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]] and [[Coniston, Cumbria|Coniston]] has long been known, but the locations of the Caldbeck mines have not. The lead-copper mines at [[Roughtengill]] have been considered to be the most probable candidates. However, recent fieldwork combined with records from archives has allowed identification of the principal mines.<ref>[http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-2055-1/dissemination/pdf/Article_Level_Pdf/tcwaas/003/2001/vol1/tcwaas_003_2001_vol1_0011.pdf The lost German mines at Caldbeck], by Richard Smith, Samuel Murphy and Warren Allison, Archaeology Data Service.</ref>
