The '''''Washington Manual of Medical Therapeutics''''' is a medical textbook first published in 1942 by Wayland MacFarlane, a [[professor]] at the [[Washington University School of Medicine]] and chief of the internal medicine ward. Described as the "bible of the medical ward" the Washington Manual of Medical Therapeutics is now in its Thirty-Fifth Edition and currently it is now the best-selling medical textbook in the world, with more than 200,000 copies worldwide. It has been translated into numerous languages including [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and both simplified and classical [[Chinese language|Chinese]]. The book's current editors are Hilary E.L. Reno, Daniel H. Cooper, Andrew J. Krainik, and Sam J. Lubner.

